default&#xa0;
defaultThis submission will address one specific aspect of the Inquiry
default terms of reference
default: 
default&#xa0;
default“The Spending Review announced in June 2013 covers the 2015/16 financial year only. What discussions can take place in the final year of the current Parliament to prepare
default for the next Spending Review?
default 
defaultWhat scope is there for future Spending Reviews to more closely mirror the term of a Parliament?”
default&#xa0;
defaultThe submission will widen the scope slightly of this question, to include how Spending Reviews and the whole Finance and Suppl
defaulty system might be impacted by the changes introduced by the FTP Act.
default&#xa0;
defaultSPENDING REVIEWS AND BUDGETS
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is 
defaultvery 
defaultimportant to be clear about the status of Spending Reviews. They are simply ‘statements of intent’ by the government, in effect 
defaultthey have
default the sam
defaulte status as a White Paper. They are not authorised by Parliament and, apart from the short-lived Fiscal Responsibility Act of Feb 2010
default, Spending Reviews had no legal basis or force.
default&#xa0;
defaultEach SR only attains real force when it is implemented through subsequen
defaultt annual Budgets
default. One problematic issue has been that Budgets – and subsequent Supply motions – do not always follow what was set out in the Spending Review for the relevant year. Moreover Governments do not make it clear when they are deviating from the p
defaultlan set out in the preceding Spending Review.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the latter years of the Labour government, and under the Coalition, this situation has become even more complicated as governments have increasingly used the Pre Budget Report (or ‘Autumn Statement’) to mak
defaulte changes to both tax and spending policies
default, increasingly looking like a mini-budget
default.
default 
defaultAs 
defaultAlistair Darling, Chancellor of the Exchequer from 2007 to 2010, remarks that “during my time as Chancellor I had to deliver what were in effect six Budgets”
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultSPENDING REVIEWS – THE STORY SO FAR
default&#xa0;
defaultOn its election in 1997 the New Labour Government announced it was introducing multi-year ‘Spending Reviews’, the first of which would be published 
defaultin the following year
default (1998)
default. These would provide the public spending 
defaultframework for a 3-year period ahead.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe aims of this innovation were several:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe idea of Governments adopting a medium-term expenditure framework 
defaultis not 
defaultespecially 
defaultnew –
default the World Bank and IMF had
default been promoting this idea to developing countries for many years before the UK decided to experiment with 
defaultit. However few OECD countries had adopted such a reform at the time and there was therefore a great
default deal of interest in the British experiment.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs promised, Labour duly published its first “Comprehensive Spending Review”
default in J
defaultuly 1998, setting out departmental budgets for the next three fiscal years (1999-2000 to 2001-02).
default Since then there have been si
defaultx further Spending Reviews, four under Labour and two under the Coalition. These are set out in 
defaultFigure 
default1
default).
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure default1default The History of Spending defaultReviewsdefaultSpending review – 
