defaultThis is of course what has more or less happened in the current Parliament. The 3 or 2-year period is also what has happened in practice in the 7 Spending Reviews since 1998. So in a sense, this would be nothing new - it would simply codi
defaultfy 
defaultand regularise 
defaultwhat has evolved in practice
default and seems to work
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultSpending Reviews could be published in draft form and subjected to Parliamentary scrutiny via the Select Codefaultmmittee system.default&#xa0;defaultOne of the issues not discussed so far is the degree to which SRs have, in practice
default, concentrated even more power in the hands of HM Treasury. Few observers would dissent from the view that they have given HMT and the Chancellor much greater control over departmental budgets. Even devices like the much vaunted ‘end-year-flexibility’ have
default been operated within tight Treasury reins. Moreover the whole spending process has been just as – if not more –secretive than before, and with less justification. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn past Budget day announcements could move markets, because 
defaultthe overall fiscal stance of 
defaultthe Government was announced alongside detailed spending and tax plans. This was at least some justification for Budget ‘purdah’. However, since SRs were introduced the Government sets out its broad fiscal position in the Autumn Statement preceding the SR 
default– announcing the size of the public spending cake to be fought over in the SR. The SR announcement simply says how the cake is to be divided up after an almost completely hidden decision process. It has no effect on markets.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs I have been arguing since t
defaulthe early 2000s, 
defaultthe 
defaultinnovation
default of Spending Reviews should have provided the opportunity
default to open this whole process up and
default for improved Parliamentary scrutiny of spending plans.
default The process should be fairly 
defaultstraightforward
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government publishes a draf
defaultt Spending Review
default,
default within the parameters 
defaultfor a public spending envelope set out in the
default preceding Autumn Statement. Each departmental Select Committee looks in detail at proposals for spending in its area. They invite evidence and opinion from interested pa
defaultrties.
default Each
default can then
default 
defaultreport
default, 
defaultbased on the evidence presented, 
defaultmaking recommendations to amend, or not, proposed spending plans.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis would go
default a long way
default towards alleviating what King and Crewe
default recently called the “deficit of deliberation” i
defaultn public 
defaultpolicy decision-making – of which public spending decisions are arguably one of the most important.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll main Pdefaultarties Spending defaultand Finance defaultproposals could be subject to scrutiny by the OBR before General Electionsdefault&#xa0;
defaultLabour has recently proposed that the OBR
default be involved in auditing the spending plans of all the main Parties in the run up to the next GE. This idea was welcomed by the Chair of the OBR and Public Accounts Committee 
defaultwhen they spoke recently in 
defaultManchester.
default&#xa0;
defaultAgain, there se
defaultems to be a fairly obvious time-
defaulttable for this. At the time of the Pre-Budget report (usually November) before the year of a GE, the main opposition Party or Parties should be invited to outline their approach to the first SR of the next parliament
default, includ
defaulting spending and fiscal policies. In the event of there being a Coalition government 
defaultin office
default, this would also be the time when the Coalition partners could – if they wised – set out their independent tax and spend policies.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe OBR should then be tasked
default with assessing the policy statement and producing a report on each at the time of the March Budget, shortly before the formal GE process begins.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAligning defaultGovernmentdefault financial statements.default&#xa0;
defaultAn important technical change would be helpful alongside these pr
defaultocedural changes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDespite HM Treasury’s so-called ‘alignment project’ it is still difficul
defaultt for Parliamentarians and members
default of the public to “follow the money” 
defaultthrough the various stages of public spending decisions: Spending Reviews; Budgets; Finance a
defaultnd Supply; and finally departmental (and whole of government) accounts. If we are to have a more integrated and predictable public spending decision-making process it is essential more progress is made on this front.
default&#xa0;
defaultCONCLUSION
default&#xa0;
defaultThe benefits of a Fixed-Te
defaultrm Parliament should not be limited to the political realm – it should also help to improve government. Fundamental to this would be to have a more ordered, predictable and open decision making process for public spending and fiscal policy. The fact that s
defaultuccessive Governments, of different complexions and in very different circumstances have found the idea of some form of medium
default-term framework helpful suggests it is useful. Fixed term Parliaments opens an opportunity to make it even more so.
